properties.NAME: White River Marsh
properties.blurb1: On November 20, 1989 in Green Lake and Marquette Counties, this fire burned 4,261 acres. Strong winds over blew a can of charcoal a hunter was using to keep warm which ignited this wildfire.

properties.NAME: Germann Road
properties.blurb1: On May 14, 2013 the Germann Road fire burned a path 10 miles long, and about 1.5 miles wide before being contained the following day. The Wisconsin DNR released that ignition was started unintentionally by a logging crew, and then spread across 8,000 acr
properties.blurb2: Logging operations surrounded by woody debri and low hanging branches of jack pine allowed the fire to hit the crowns and spread through the dense forest in minutes.

properties.NAME: Brockway
properties.blurb1: The Brockway fire ignited on April 27th, 1977 four miles east of Black River Falls due to a train setting fires to the nearby foliage. Multiple small fires combined to form the larger Brockway fire, which burned over 17 thousand acres of land and caused
properties.blurb2: Firefighting equipment was tough to come by for the Brockway fire due to the Saratoga fire igniting on the same day. Tractor plows were used to fight the fires, and even those were scarce. The fire was finally controlled at 2:15 am on April 28th.

properties.NAME: Ekdall Church
properties.blurb1: A fire caused by accidental actions, the Ekdall Church ignited on April 21st, 1980. With a fire front of over 2.5 miles in length, the fire tore through 4,654 acres of land before being contained.
properties.blurb2: It took 7 fire departments, 15 DNR tractor plows and almost 30 bulldozers from both public and private organizations, not to mention countless volunteers, to take down the fire. 65 buildings were saved through the heroic efforts of these people.

properties.NAME: West Marshland
properties.blurb1: The winter of 1958-59 had all but no snow accumulation, leading to conditions extremely susceptible to wildfire. Just as firefighters predicted, on May 1st, 1959, the West Marshland fire started, and before its complete control on the night of May 2nd, i
properties.blurb2: The preparedness of the local police and fire departments proved crucial. With all hands on deck from 4 different counties, the fire was eventually under control and denied much more damage to the extremely fire prone area.

properties.NAME: Oak Lake
properties.blurb1: On April 22nd, 1980 this fire burned 11,500 acres across a 13 mile path.  A cause was never determined for this fire which is one of the states largest wildfires. Over 150 structures including residences were destroyed.
properties.blurb2: The fire started 11 miles west of Oak Lake, Wisconsin, and smoke was visible from over 90 miles away before the fire was contained in an effort taking 2000 firemen.

properties.NAME: Crystal Lake
properties.blurb1: In Marquette and Waushara County, this fire burned 572 acres on April 13 2003. Debri was ignited by a man at the Lake of the Woods Campground in northern Waushara County. This smoldered for weeks before being reignited by somebody adding fuel on a day wi
properties.blurb2: A jury has found the campground negligent and awarded more than $630,000 in damages mainly to property owners.

properties.NAME: Saratoga
properties.blurb1: April 27th, 1977 is the day that both the Brockway and Saratoga fires ignited. An especially windy day with low levels of humidity pushed this fire east and south to burn a total of 6,159 acres of land.
properties.blurb2: Over 100 men and women worked to suppress the fire, finally getting it under control around 11:00 pm and saving approximately 300 buildings. Still, over $1 million dollars worth of damage was done.

properties.NAME: Five Mile Tower
properties.blurb1: The spring of 1977 was a troubling one for fires in Wisconsin, and the Five Mile Tower fire was no exception. On April 30th, the same day as the Airport fire, a spark from a campfire turned a pine forest into flames that englufed over 13,000 acres of lan
properties.blurb2: While 83 buildings perished in the fire, the control effort managed to save over 300 buildings from the chaos. The control effort consisted not only of firefighters stopping the fire in its tracks, but also individual homeowners taking precautionary meas

properties.NAME: Cottonville
properties.blurb1: On May 5th, 2005, Cottonville, Wisconsin of Adams County the Cottonville fire was ignited burning 3,400 acres across a 10 mile stretch. Dozens of structures were destroyed and 30 homes in total. A man was clearing his land in order to make it less suscep
properties.blurb2: Charges were filed against the man who spent 90 days in jail and two years on probation, with the total amount of restitution owed being $1,436,504.

properties.NAME: Airport
properties.blurb1: Without giving the firefighting crew any break, a chainsaw burst into flames, and a fire, now called the Airport fire, ignited on April 30th, 1977, just days after both the Brockway and Saratoga fires had been contained. 1,500 people were forced to evacu
properties.blurb2: A total of 3,037 acres of land were burned by the fire. A monumental effort made by 63 different fire departments made sure that not a single building was lost during the fire.

properties.NAME: Peshtigo
properties.blurb1: The deadliest fire in American History happened in the state of Wisconsin on October 8th, 1871. The town of Peshtigo, just north of Green Bay, was completely destroyed, and with it wiping out a population of over 1,200. Over 1,200,000 acres were burned on both the Door Peninsula and directly west of it across Green Bay.
properties.blurb2: The fire is said to have totalled damages worth upwards of $169 million dollars. The infamous Chicago Fire of 1871 occurred on the same day, so the Peshtigo fire is relatively unknown, despite burning an area almost double the size of the state of Rhode Island.
